sburg, shedding light on the remarkable diversity of American religion and the intricate ways it interacted with the broader culture. Longenecker argues that Gettysburg religion revealed much about larger American society and about how trends in the Border North mirrored national developments. In many ways, Gettysburg and its surrounding Border North religion belonged to the future and signaled a coming pattern for modern America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aReligion and culturezPennsylvaniazGettysburg RegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aReligion and culturezPennsylvaniazGettysburgxHistoryy19th century. 4aAfrican American (Black). 4aCivil War. 4aCivil religion. 4aDiversity. 4aEvangelicalism. 4aGettysburg. 4aLutheran. 4aPennsylvania. 4aRace. 4arefinement. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823255214zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823255214423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823255214.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK